817	270	t	2011-08-12 19:16:54	Patrick	patrick@patshaping.de		<p>I know this blog posting is older, I hope you will answer my comment.</p>\n\n<p>First of all: It sounds interesting.<br>\nBut isn't forum data something you usually store in a classical RDBMS? A forum posting usually has a thread ID, a posting ID, the parent posting's ID, the author's name and some other data, timestamps and the posting text. That's something I would store in a RDBMS.<br>\nPlease don't misunderstand me: I think you're much more into CouchDB and especially Classic Forum and so you know what you're doing. I'm just interested why a document-oriented storage fits Classic Forum's needs. I don't get it from what you're writing.</p>	nATlyIm1313152721OTVWftA
818	270	t	2011-08-12 22:47:33	Christian Kruse			<p>Last comment before holidays! ;-)</p>\n\n<p>One forum posting is something you can be saved relatively well in a RDBMS. A whole thread is a problem: either you count on proprietary features to save hierarchical data or you use something like nested trees to save the hierarchy. First variant is often not very elegant implemented and second is really slow when you save a new answer.</p>\n\n<p>Also, to save various metadata for a thread (e.g. „moderated,“ „no answer,“ „now index“ etc pp) you can either use a key value table or you have a table with LOTS of columns.</p>\n\n<p>Both problems simply don't exist in a document based DBMS. You can save hierarchical data without a problem (simply use nested JSON objects and/or arrays) and you can save any key value pairs in the structure w/o changing the schema and w/o using something ugly like a key value table.</p>\n\n<p>Also, the natural access to postings is the access through it's primary key. This is exactly, what a document based DBMS is very good at.</p>\n\n<p>See ya in three weeks :)</p>	9FJdL7z13131815753zqD46I
